      "role": "user",
      "content": "it's not even one single thing. it's just... everything. i try to fix it, i try to be better, i try to stay sober, i try to work, and it just ends the same way every single time. it feels like no matter what i do, the outcome is already decided. it's just a pattern i can't escape. like i'm just waiting for the inevitable.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It sounds incredibly draining to feel like your efforts are futile and that the outcome is predetermined, regardless of what you do. That sense of helplessness can be overwhelming, especially when you're trying so hard to stay sober and improve your life.\n\nSometimes, when we feel like we're trapped in a loop, it's not because the pattern is unbreakable, but because we might be trying to control too much at once. You mentioned trying to \"fix it\" and \"be better\"—that can sometimes add more pressure than relief. Have you ever considered that stepping back from the pressure to \"fix everything\" might actually allow you to break the cycle?\n\nIt's okay to feel stuck right now, but you don't have to carry the weight of the entire pattern alone. Would you be open to talking about what happens right before those moments of falling apart? Understanding the specific sequence of events, even the small ones, can sometimes reveal a point where you have a choice.",
